# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: auslan
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] The plot concerns Reuben (played by Davo Hardy), who overcomes a speech impediment with the use of Auslan, with help from his profoundly deaf boyfriend (played by Joshua Sealy).
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Having built up Reuben's confidence enough to encourage his higher ambitions, Derek contacts an Australian screen legend, Gareth (played by Paul Mercurio) to help mentor Reuben in his burgeoning career.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] But shortly after seeing the potential in Reuben's autobiographical screenplay, Gareth takes over the project for his own gain and sanitizes the story to suit a wider audience, thereby cutting Reuben out of the equation.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Forced to draw upon the courage and self-actualization that he has gathered through the experience, Reuben stands up to his bully and wins the support of those who had once opposed him, for the greater moral good.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Davo Hardy has stated in interviews that the film was a response to his film mentors telling him he could not be a director because of his real-life stutter.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Reuben Heywood is an aspiring writer, who grapples with anxiety, manifesting as a stutter, while attempting to build a career as both a writer and actor.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] When a performance at an amateur theatre showcase goes awry, Reuben is bullied by the troupe leader and a sign language interpreter.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Derek Shanahan, a profoundly deaf man from the audience (played by Joshua Sealy) comes to vindicate him and the two form a friendship which quickly turns into a sexual relationship.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] As Derek and Reuben discuss their mutual ambitions within the arts and political activism, Reuben discloses his troubled past and the origins of his speech impediment.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Derek encourages Reuben to steer his work away from theater and into independent film, offering to support him, where needed.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Shortly after, Derek seeks out Reuben's dream mentor, Gareth Donahue (played by Paul Mercurio) to help him bring his story, titled *The Burden of Being Me* to the screen.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Gareth, meanwhile, has reached a low point in his career.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] He is over 50, lamenting his lost youth and fading career.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Hungry for a chance to make a comeback, Gareth agrees to meet with Reuben and discuss their collaboration on *The Burden of Being Me*.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Derek is also present at the meeting and is quick to point out Gareth's self-obsessed narcissism. but Reuben overlooks his observations, blindsided by the support that Gareth offers.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Derek's mother, Faye Shanahan, and sister, Courtney, are deeply protective of Derek and treat Reuben's artistic ambitions with skepticism.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Faye, a painter, discourages Derek's involvement with Reuben's filmmaking, in favor of noble causes to support deaf education and advocating human rights in the footsteps of Helen Keller.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Reuben recognizes the hypocrisy and continues to pursue his film with Derek and Gareth.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Almost immediately after receiving the script of *The Burden of Being Me*, Gareth begins to amend the characters and plot to suit him as both an actor and a producer.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] His wife, Lillian Donahue, a highly respected entertainment attorney, is captivated by the screenplay and recognizes Reuben as a talented writer.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] But Gareth uses his industry expertise and gas-lighting tactics to seize creative control from Reuben, while also manipulating Lillian to help him, using her long-delayed desire to have children as leverage for emotional blackmail.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Obediently, Lillian writes up contracts that highly favor Gareth's interests and leave Reuben empty handed.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Immediately conflicted by guilt, Lillian stands idly by, as Gareth pressures Reuben to sign the contracts and grant him 100% of the rights.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] When Reuben realizes that he has been swindled, Faye offers to help finance Reuben's next project, effectively giving her blessing for he and Derek to collaborate in the future.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] This offer is quickly retracted when Reuben accidentally makes a spectacle of himself at Courtney's engagement party and embarrasses the family.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Derek sides with Faye, citing that Reuben has acted in appropriately.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Reuben is asked to leave the party, at once.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Shortly after, Reuben receives an emotional call from Courtney, saying that Derek has suddenly died from an accident.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] At the funeral, Faye confronts Reuben, imploring him to continue honoring Derek's memory, but also to honor himself.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Meanwhile, Lillian reads an article about Reuben's stage play, dedicated to Derek's memory.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Gareth's only response is to make sure the stage play has no affiliation with the film he now owns the rights to, or else they'd have to sue.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Incensed at Gareth's heartlessness, Lillian lashes out at him and vows to reverse the contracts that she had made for Gareth.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Concluding that her chance to have children has passed her by, Lillian abandons Gareth and seeks Reuben out at the theater, where he and Derek met.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] She encourages him to rewrite his story from scratch and amend key elements, so that Gareth cannot claim copyright infringement.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Similarly, Faye reinstates her support of Reuben, around the time of her first Christmas since her son's death.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] One by one, Gareth's collaborators abandon his project and he is left without any supporters at around the time that Reuben develops his new film, *The Purpose of Being Me*.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] At the a screening of his film, Reuben thanks the audience for attending, including those who may have originally discouraged him.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] He thanks them for providing the strength he needed to continue in his pursuits, even if it was only to prove them wrong.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] The film also brought Paul Mercurio back into the spotlight.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] On 11 April 2017, during a live interview for *The Morning Show*, the hosts Larry Emdur and Kylie Gillies attempted to discuss the 25-year anniversary of *Strictly Ballroom*, but Paul continued to steer the conversation back to *A Silent Agreement*.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] He was cast in *Promised* a few months later.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] The film was submitted into many festivals for its use of Auslan, qualifying it as a foreign language film.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Many LGBT-related festivals and organisations to do with the deaf and disabilities were lauding of *A Silent Agreement* for its authentic depictions of deaf characters, using deaf actors.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] The DVD was released in Australia on 8 December 2018, after its extended festival screenings; including special seminar screenings for its educational importance in support of Auslan and speech pathology.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] LGBT streaming service Dekkoo began to distribute the film from June 2019.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] Amazon released an NTSC DVD in September 2019.
[src:auslan/a-silent-agreement] From 2022, *A Silent Agreement*, along with the rest of Davo Hardy's films, were made available on his dedicated streaming website; www.davohardyfilms.com.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] An **abbreviation** (from Latin **brevis** 'short') is a shortened form of a word or phrase, by any method including shortening, contraction, initialism (which includes acronym), or crasis.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] An abbreviation may be a shortened form of a word, usually ended with a trailing full stop (period).
[src:auslan/abbreviation] For example, the term *etc.* is the usual abbreviation for the Latin phrase *et cetera*.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] A *contraction* is an abbreviation formed by leaving out letters or sounds, typically replaced by an apostrophe in English.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Examples include *I'm* for *I am* and *li'l* for *little*.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] An *initialism* or *acronym* is an abbreviation consisting of the initial letter of a sequence of words without other punctuation.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] For example, FBI (/ˌɛf.biːˈaɪ/), USA (/ˌjuː.ɛsˈeɪ/), IBM (/ˌaɪ.biːˈɛm/), BBC (/ˌbiː.biːˈsiː/).
[src:auslan/abbreviation] When initialism is used as the preferred term, acronym refers more specifically to when the abbreviation is pronounced as a word rather than as separate letters; examples include SWAT and NASA.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Initialisms, contractions and crasis share some semantic and phonetic functions, and are connected by the term *abbreviation* in loose parlance.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] In early times, abbreviations may have been common due to the effort involved in writing (many inscriptions were carved in stone) or to provide secrecy via obfuscation.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Reduction of a word to a single letter was common in both Greek and Roman writing.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] In Roman inscriptions, "Words were commonly abbreviated by using the initial letter or letters of words, and most inscriptions have at least one abbreviation".
[src:auslan/abbreviation] However, "some could have more than one meaning, depending on their context.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Abbreviations were frequently used in early English.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Manuscripts of copies of the Old English poem *Beowulf* used many abbreviations, for example the Tironian et (⁊) or & for *and*, and y for *since*, so that "not much space is wasted".
[src:auslan/abbreviation] The standardisation of English in the 15th through 17th centuries included a growth in the use of such abbreviations.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] At first, abbreviations were sometimes represented with various suspension signs, not only periods.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] For example, sequences like ⟨er⟩ were replaced with ⟨ɔ⟩, as in mastɔ for *master* and exacɔbate for *exacerbate*.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] While this may seem trivial, it was symptomatic of an attempt by people manually reproducing academic texts to reduce the copy time.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] — Warden of Merton College, University of Oxford in *Registrum Annalium Collegii Mertonensis*, 1503.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] In the Early Modern English period, between the 15th and 17th centuries, the thorn Þ was used for *th*, as in Þe ('the').
[src:auslan/abbreviation] In modern times, ⟨Þ⟩ was often used (in the form ⟨y⟩) for promotional reasons, as in Ye Olde Tea Shoppe.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] During the growth of philological linguistic theory in academic Britain, abbreviating became very fashionable.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Likewise, a century earlier in Boston, a fad of abbreviation started that swept the United States, with the globally popular term OK generally credited as a remnant of its influence.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Over the years, however, the lack of convention in some style guides has made it difficult to determine which two-word abbreviations should be abbreviated with periods and which should not.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Widespread use of electronic communication through mobile phones and the Internet during the 1990s led to a marked rise in colloquial abbreviation.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] This was due largely to increasing popularity of textual communication services such as instant and text messaging.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] The original SMS supported message lengths of 160 characters at most (using the GSM 03.38 character set), for instance.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] This brevity gave rise to an informal abbreviation scheme sometimes called Textese, with which 10% or more of the words in a typical SMS message are abbreviated.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] More recently Twitter, a popular social networking service, began driving abbreviation use with 140 character message limits.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] In HTML, abbreviations can be annotated using a dedicated tag: `<abbr title="Editor">Ed.</abbr>` In this example, the meaning of "Ed." as "Editor" is revealed by hovering the cursor over it.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] In modern English, there are multiple conventions for abbreviation, and there is controversy as to which should be used.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] One generally accepted rule is to be consistent in a body of work.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] To this end, publishers may express their preferences in a style guide.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Some controversies that arise are described below.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] If the original word was capitalized then the first letter of its abbreviation should retain the capital, for example Lev. for *Leviticus*.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] When a word is abbreviated to more than a single letter and was originally spelled with lower case letters then there is no need for capitalization.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] However, when abbreviating a phrase where only the first letter of each word is taken, then all letters should be capitalized, as in YTD for *year-to-date*, PCB for *printed circuit board* and FYI for *for your information*.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] However, see the following section regarding abbreviations that have become common vocabulary: these are no longer written with capital letters.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] A period (full stop) is sometimes used to signify abbreviation, but opinion is divided as to when and if this convention is best practice.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] According to Hart's Rules, a word shortened by dropping letters from the end terminates with a full stop (period), whereas a word shorted by dropping letters from the middle does not.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Fowler's Modern English Usage says a full stop (period) is used for both of these shortened forms, but recommends against this practice.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] It advises it only for end-shortened words and lower-case initialisms, not for middle-shortened words and upper-case initialisms.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Some British style guides, such as for The Guardian and The Economist, disallow periods for all abbreviations.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] In American English, the period is usually included regardless of whether or not it is a contraction, e.g.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] *Dr.* or *Mrs.* In some cases, periods are optional, as in either *US* or *U.S.* for *United States*, *EU* or *E.U.* for *European Union*, and *UN* or *U.N.* for *United Nations*.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] There are some house styles, however—American ones included—that remove the periods from almost all abbreviations.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Acronyms that were originally capitalized (with or without periods) but have since entered the vocabulary as generic words are no longer written with capital letters nor with any periods.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Examples are sonar, radar, lidar, laser, snafu, and scuba.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] In the past, some initialisms were styled with a period after each letter and a space between each pair.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] There are multiple ways to pluralize an abbreviation.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Sometimes this accomplished by adding an apostrophe and an *s* ('s), as in "two PC's have broken screens".
[src:auslan/abbreviation] But, some find this confusing since the notation can indicate possessive case.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] And, this style is deprecated by many style guides.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] For instance, Kate Turabian, writing about style in academic writings, allows for an apostrophe to form plural acronyms "only when an abbreviation contains internal periods or both capital and lowercase letters".
[src:auslan/abbreviation] For example, "DVDs" and "URLs" and "Ph.D.'s", while the Modern Language Association explicitly says, "do not use an apostrophe to form the plural of an abbreviation".
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Also, the American Psychological Association specifically says, "without an apostrophe".
[src:auslan/abbreviation] However, the 1999 style guide for *The New York Times* states that the addition of an apostrophe is necessary when pluralizing all abbreviations, preferring "PC's, TV's and VCR's".
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Forming a plural of an initialization without an apostrophe can also be used for a number, or a letter.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] For units of measure, the same form is used for both singular and plural.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] When an abbreviation contains more than one period, *Hart's Rules* recommends putting the *s* after the final one.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] According to *Hart's Rules*, an apostrophe may be used in rare cases where clarity calls for it, for example when letters or symbols are referred to as objects.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] In Latin, and continuing to the derivative forms in European languages as well as English, single-letter abbreviations had the plural being a doubling of the letter for note-taking.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Most of these deal with writing and publishing.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] A few longer abbreviations use this as well.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Publications based in the U.S. tend to follow the style guides of *The Chicago Manual of Style* and the Associated Press.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] The U.S. government follows a style guide published by the U.S.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] The National Institute of Standards and Technology sets the style for abbreviations of units.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Writers often use shorthand to denote units of measure.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Such shorthand can be an abbreviation, such as "in" for "inch" or can be a symbol such as "km" for "kilometre".
[src:auslan/abbreviation] In the International System of Units (SI) manual the word "symbol" is used consistently to define the shorthand used to represent the various SI units of measure.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] A syllabic abbreviation is usually formed from the initial syllables of several words, such as *Interpol* = *International* + *police*.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are usually written using lower case, sometimes starting with a capital letter, and are always pronounced as words rather than letter by letter.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations should be distinguished from portmanteaus, which combine two words without necessarily taking whole syllables from each.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are not widely used in English.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Some UK government agencies such as Ofcom (Office of Communications) and the former Oftel (Office of Telecommunications) use this style.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] New York City has various neighborhoods named by syllabic abbreviation, such as Tribeca (Triangle below Canal Street) and SoHo (South of Houston Street).
[src:auslan/abbreviation] This usage has spread into other American cities, giving SoMa, San Francisco (South of Market), and LoDo, Denver (Lower Downtown), amongst others.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Sections of California are also often colloquially syllabically abbreviated, as in NorCal (Northern California), CenCal (Central California), and SoCal (Southern California).
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Additionally, in the context of Los Angeles, the syllabic abbreviation SoHo (Southern Hollywood) refers to the southern portion of the Hollywood neighborhood.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Partially syllabic abbreviations are preferred by the US Navy, as they increase readability amidst the large number of initialisms that would otherwise have to fit into the same acronyms.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Hence *DESRON 6* is used (in the full capital form) to mean "Destroyer Squadron 6", while *COMNAVAIRLANT* would be "Commander, Naval Air Force (in the) Atlantic".
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are a prominent feature of Newspeak, the fictional language of George Orwell's dystopian novel *Nineteen Eighty-Four*.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] The political contractions of Newspeak—*Ingsoc* (English Socialism), *Minitrue* (Ministry of Truth), *Miniplenty* (Ministry of Plenty)—are described by Orwell as similar to real examples of German *(see below)* and Russian (*see below)* contractions in the 20th century.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] The contractions in Newspeak are supposed to have a political function by virtue of their abbreviated structure itself: nice sounding and easily pronounceable, their purpose is to mask all ideological content from the speaker.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] A more recent syllabic abbreviation has emerged with the disease COVID-19 (Corona Virus Disease 2019) caused by the Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (itself frequently abbreviated to SARS-CoV-2, partly an initialism).
[src:auslan/abbreviation] In Albanian, syllabic acronyms are sometimes used for composing a person's name, such as *Migjeni*—an abbreviation from his original name (*Millosh Gjergj Nikolla*) a famous Albanian poet and writer—or *ASDRENI* (*Aleksander Stavre Drenova*), another famous Albanian poet.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Other such names which are used commonly in recent decades are GETOAR, composed from *Gegeria* + *Tosks* (representing the two main dialects of the Albanian language, Gegë and Toskë), and *Arbanon*—which is an alternative way used to describe all Albanian lands.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations were and are common in German; much like acronyms in English, they have a distinctly modern connotation, although contrary to popular belief, many date back to before 1933, if not the end of the Great War.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] *Kriminalpolizei*, literally *criminal police* but idiomatically the Criminal Investigation Department of any German police force, begat *KriPo* (variously capitalised), and likewise *Schutzpolizei* (*protection police* or *uniform department*) begat *SchuPo*.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Along the same lines, the Swiss Federal Railways' Transit Police—the *Transportpolizei*—are abbreviated as the *TraPo*.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] With the National Socialist German Workers' Party gaining power came a frenzy of government reorganisation, and with it a series of entirely new syllabic abbreviations.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Non regime-aligned partially syllabic abbreviations also existed like "Gröfaz" for the self-proclaimed "größter Feldherr aller Zeiten" (greatest military commander of all time), i.e.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] The new order of the German Democratic Republic in the east brought about a conscious denazification, but also a repudiation of earlier turns of phrase in favour of neologisms such as *Stasi* for *Staatssicherheit* ("state security", the secret police) and *VoPo* for *Volkspolizei*.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] The phrase *politisches Büro*, which may be rendered literally as "office of politics" or idiomatically as "political party steering committee", became *Politbüro*.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are not only used in politics, however.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are very common in Russian, Belarusian and Ukrainian.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] They are often used as names of organizations.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Historically, popularization of abbreviations was a way to simplify mass-education in 1920s (see Likbez).
[src:auslan/abbreviation] The word *kolkhoz* (*kollektívnoye khozyáystvo*, collective farm) is another example.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Leninist organisations such as the *Comintern* (*Communist International*) and *Komsomol* (*Kommunisticheskii Soyuz Molodyozhi*, or "Communist youth union") used Russian language syllabic abbreviations.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] In the modern Russian language, words like *Rosselkhozbank* (from Rossiysky selskokhozyaystvenny bank — Russian Agricultural Bank, RusAg) and *Minobrnauki* (from Ministerstvo obrazovaniya i nauki — Ministry of Education and Science) are still commonly used.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] In nearby Belarus, there are *Beltelecom* (Belarus Telecommunication) and Belsat (Belarus Satellite).
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are common in Spanish; examples abound in organization names such as Pemex for *Petróleos Mexicanos* ("Mexican Petroleums") or Fonafifo for *Fondo Nacional de Financimiento Forestal* (National Forestry Financing Fund).
[src:auslan/abbreviation] ("Banamex"), Teléfonos de México, S.A.B. de C.V.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] ("TELMEX"), Operadora de Cinemas, S.A. de C.V.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Malaysian abbreviation often uses letters from each word, while Indonesia usually uses syllables; although some cases do not follow the style.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] For example, general elections in Malaysian Malay often shortened into PRU (**p**ilihan **r**aya **u**mum) while Indonesian often shortened into pemilu (**pemil**ihan **u**mum).
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Another example is Ministry of Health in which Malaysian Malay uses KKM (**K**ementerian **K**esihatan **M**alaysia), compared to Indonesian Kemenkes (**Kemen**terian **Kes**ehatan).
[src:auslan/abbreviation] East Asian languages whose writing systems use Chinese characters form abbreviations similarly by using key Chinese characters from a term or phrase.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] For example, in Japanese the term for the United Nations, *kokusai rengō* (国際連合) is often abbreviated to *kokuren* (国連).
[src:auslan/abbreviation] (Such abbreviations are called ryakugo (略語) in Japanese; see also Japanese abbreviated and contracted words).
[src:auslan/abbreviation] The syllabic abbreviation of kanji words is frequently used for universities: for instance, *Tōdai* (東大) for *Tōkyō daigaku* (東京大学, University of Tokyo) and is used similarly in Chinese: *Běidà* (北大) for *Běijīng Dàxué* (北京大学, Peking University).
[src:auslan/abbreviation] Korean universities often follow the same conventions, such as *Hongdae* (홍대) as short for *Hongik Daehakgyo*, or Hongik University.
[src:auslan/abbreviation] The English phrase "Gung ho" originated as a Chinese abbreviation.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] As the primary news division of the ABC, it is responsible for all news-gathering and coverage across the public broadcaster's various television, radio, and online platforms.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] ABC News has an extensive online presence which includes written news reports and videos, an ABC News mobile app (ABC Listen), podcasts, and in addition, all of the ABC News television programs available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment, and news in other languages.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] Simon Robinson was appointed director of the division on 28 May 2026.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] ABC News, from its inception in 1932, with ABC radio sourced its news from multiple sources, including cable news from London, its own bureaus in Europe, the Middle East and the Asia-Pacific, and in a fashion similar to commercial radio stations from local newspapers around Australia.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] Censorship was rife during the war, particularly after the U.S. entered the conflict on 7 December 1941.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] After General Douglas MacArthur set up his headquarters in Australia, he wielded enormous power, including on matters of censorship.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] Inter alia, he declared that every Australian radio station would only broadcast three news bulletins per day and that these would be simultaneous on all stations (ABC and commercial) at 7.45 a.m., midday, and 7.00 p.m.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] Weather forecasts were banned because it was felt that these may assist the enemy.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] The 7:45 a.m. bulletin was the only one that did not commence on the hour or the half-hour.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] It was placed at this timeslot as initially the ABC sourced its news from newspapers in a deal which required that news would not be broadcast earlier, to ensure newspapers sales were not affected.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] This bulletin continued at this time on ABC Local Radio stations until 19 September 2020, before being cancelled to save costs.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] Notices were issued banning radio stations from broadcasting some major wartime events, but as the federal government did not have the same power over the printed press as it did over the radio, newspapers usually reported events that radio was not permitted to mention.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] The ABC launched its first independent news bulletin on 1 June 1947 after years of negotiations with the Australian Government.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] The *Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983* mandates that the ABC "shall develop and maintain an independent service for the broadcasting of news and information" both within Australia on a daily basis, and also to countries outside Australia.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] The name of the division and director responsible has changed over the years.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] In 2004 it was the News and Current Affairs Division when John Cameron took over as Director from Max Uechtritz as Director.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] The financial year 2008–2009 saw a lot of changes, both in the way that television content was produced as well as an "expansion of international news programming and continuous news across platforms, new programs and a range of appointments to senior positions".
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] Kate Torney became director of the News Division in April 2009.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] In November 2014, a cut of A$254 million to funding over the following five years meant that the ABC would have to shed about 10% of its total staff, around 400 people.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] There were several programming changes, with regional and local programming losing out to national programs, and the Adelaide TV production studio had to close apart from the news and current affairs section.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] In late 2015 Gaven Morris was appointed Director of the News Division.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] On 10 April 2017, ABC News introduced a new visual identity; as part of the changes, ABC News 24 and ABC NewsRadio were both rebranded as simply "ABC News", while their previously-separate social media presences were merged and unified under ABC News accounts.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] The Director's role changed its name to Director, News, Analysis & Investigations in 2017–2018, and as of June 2021 Morris was still in the role.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] During the 2017 to 2018 financial year, the ABC launched "Regional Connecting Communities" program, which provided funding for increased jobs in the regions, as well as more resources for local news, weather and live reporting.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] Justin Stevens was appointed director of the division of ABC News, Analysis and Investigations on 31 March 2022.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] Media executive and producer Kimberly Lynton "Kim" Williams AM was appointed chair of ABC News on 7 March 2024, with the term expected to conclude on 6 March 2029.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] In March 2026, staff at ABC began a one-day strike over pay and working conditions.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] This was the first walk out in 20 years.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] The division is responsible for all news-gathering and production of news output for ABC television, the ABC network of radio stations, and for its online services.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] In 2018 it was estimated that online ABC news and current affairs reached about 4.8 million users in Australia each month.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment and news in other languages.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] The news theme used from the first days of ABC television from November 1956 to 1985 was "Majestic Fanfare", composed by Charles Williams.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] From 1956 until the early 1980s the version used was the abridged version performed by the Queen's Hall Light Orchestra, from a recording made in 1943.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] Each bulletin opened with a clip from the top story of the day, with the title "ABC News" superimposed over the footage.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] Later, this on-screen approach was replaced by a generic graphic title sequence.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] In 1982, to celebrate the ABC's 50th anniversary, a new version of the theme was commissioned, which incorporated both orchestral and new electronic elements.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] With the exception of a period in the mid-1980s, during which a synthesised theme ("Best Endeavours", written by Alan Hawkshaw, which was the theme for Channel 4 News in the UK) was used for around a year, this was used on radio until August 1988, and on television until early 1985.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] A reworking of "Majestic Fanfare" (essentially the original orchestration up one tone) was arranged by Richard Mills and recorded in 1988 by the Sydney Symphony Orchestra.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] From 1985, a theme composed by Tony Ansell and Peter Wall was used for 20 years, even after the 1998 brand refresh.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] In 2010, it was sampled and remixed by the group Pendulum and this revised work went on to be placed #11 on the Triple J Hottest 100 chart on Australia Day 2011.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] The theme for ABC News changed on Australia Day (26 January) 2005, to a piece written by Martin Armiger and John Gray, and for a couple of years it bore a resemblance to the original Peter Wall / Tony Ansell work in the opening signature notes.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] Wall challenged the ABC and was successful in reaching an agreement.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] The opening notes were removed and the work was re-arranged in 2010.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] The theme music from the 2005–2010 era was remixed by Armiger, giving it a more upbeat, synthesised feel.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] In August 2024, the Ansell–Wall theme was revived in an updated form as part of a larger rebranding of ABC News.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] The theme was remastered by David McDonald from the original multi-track studio recording, including a rerecorded piccolo, and layered samples of a children's drumkit (which McDonald had originally bought for his daughter) to add a bassier sound.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] On 4 March 1985, the ABC refreshed its structure and look, when the 7 o'clock news and the following current affairs program (at that time, *Nationwide*) were combined to form *The National*, and moved to 6:30 pm until 8 December 1985.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] After *The National* was deemed unsuccessful, On 9 December 1985, the news was refreshed again with a new set, graphics, and theme.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] In 1998, the set was updated, a new opener featuring a light blue globe and the ABC logo was introduced, and the theme remained the same but was tweaked.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] The graphics also changed to match the new look.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] On Australia Day (26 January) 2005, a new look (along with theme music) was introduced.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] The new look made use of an orange and blue globe motif.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] At the same time the set and graphics received a major overhaul to fit in with this look.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] This package was used until 21 July 2010, a day before the launch of ABC News.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] In January 2010, the ABC announced that a dedicated 24-hour digital television news channel, named ABC News 24 would be launched during the year.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] The new channel commenced preliminary broadcasting with a promo loop in early July 2010, with the ABC re-numbering ABC HD channel 20 to logical channel number 24.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] The channel was officially launched as ABC News 24 at 7:30 pm Australian Eastern Standard Time on 22 July 2010, and simulcast its first hour of transmission on ABC1.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] With the launch of ABC News on 22 July 2010, all 7 pm bulletins across Australia had a graphics overhaul to match the look of the new channel.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] The blue/orange globe style opener was replaced with a series of sliding panels, featuring images specific to each state.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] New sets were built in each capital city studio to match the ABC News 24 set and graphics were changed to match.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] The news bulletins such as *News Breakfast*, *ABC News Mornings*, *ABC News at Noon, ABC News Day,* *ABC News Afternoons*, *The World*, *ABC Late News* and *Weekend Breakfast* are aired on ABC News along with its own 30- and 15-minute hourly bulletins.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] National news updates are presented on ABC TV throughout the day, with evening updates at 7 pm presented live in most states by the respective state news presenters.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] Bulletins focus strongly on issues of state relevance, with a greater inclusion of national and international news items than are found in the news bulletins of commercial broadcasters.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] A national financial bulletin is presented on weeknights by Alan Kohler in Melbourne.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] The ABC's Ultimo studios produces the 8:30 pm weeknight update presented by Joe O'Brien.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] News and current affairs programs are also broadcast on ABC Australia, a channel broadcast to the region outside Australia.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] These include *Four Corners*, *7:30* and *Q+A*.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] ABC news television programs are available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] ABC NewsRadio is a radio station dedicated to news and current affairs.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] It features national news bulletins at :00 and :30, with rolling news coverage during the remainder of each hour.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] In off-peak hours, it broadcasts content from partner providers such as the BBC World Service, NPR, and Deutsche Welle.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] Radio Australia, which covers the Asia-Pacific region, broadcasts regular bulletins produced in Melbourne, featuring reports from foreign correspondents in the region.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] State bulletins are produced by the ABC Local Radio station from the capital city of each state and mainland territory.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] They are broadcast to all ABC Local Radio and Radio National stations in each state, and focus strongly on issues of state relevance, but also feature national and international stories.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] National bulletins air when state bulletins are not produced.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] ABC Local Radio stations previously broadcast a flagship 15-minute state bulletin at 7:45 am, which in its final years was the only bulletin still introduced by the 18-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] All other bulletins were introduced by a 9-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] This bulletin began in 1939 and was discontinued on Sunday 20 September 2020.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] ABC News produces several current affairs programs for radio.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] All share a quasi-magazine format, and investigate stories in greater depth compared to news bulletins.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] All ABC radio stations are available via an ABC News mobile app, ABC Listen, from which podcasts are also available.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] In March 2024, ABC News won the 2023 Gold Lizzie for Best Title at the IT Journalism Awards, a shared honour between ABC News Story Lab and ABC Radio.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australia] ABC News also won Best Gaming Coverage and Best News Coverage.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] The **ABC News Channel** is an Australian 24-hour news channel launched and owned by the Australian Broadcasting Corporation.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] The channel replaced and used the then-former ABC HD channel space (which simulcast ABC TV in high definition) and commenced broadcasting as **ABC News 24** at 7:30pm (AEST) on Thursday, 22 July 2010.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] The majority of the channel's content is produced from the studios of the ABC's Sydney station, ABN, in Ultimo, Sydney which the public can view being presented from an atrium looking into the news presentation studio.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] The ABC's breakfast television programme, *News Breakfast*, Afternoon Briefing and the evening programme *The World* is produced at ABV Southbank, Melbourne (weekdays).
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] Initially launched in MPEG-2 high definition, the channel's picture format reduced to standard definition on 6 December 2016, following the relaunch of ABC HD.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] The HD feed, however, gradually rolled out as an alternative option via ABC iView, the ABC News website and on Youtube; before restoring it, now in the MPEG-4 encoding format, to terrestrial viewers in June 2025.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] The ABC announced in January 2010 that it planned to launch a 24-hour news channel.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] The logo of ABC News 24 was revealed by Freeview in their new promotion on Tuesday 22 June.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] The official promotional reel for the channel was launched on digital channel 24 between 6 and 8 July.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] Speculation about a launch date for the channel took place in the weeks prior to the official announcement.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] *The Daily Telegraph* claimed in early July that the channel would be delayed due to technical issues at the ABC's new playout facility, MediaHub, in south west Sydney while other outlets reported that the channel was on track to begin in mid-July.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] The ABC announced on 13 July 2010 that the channel would have its first live broadcast on 22 July.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] In November 2016, the ABC announced that ABC News 24 and ABC NewsRadio would be rebranded under a unified ABC News brand.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] On 22 July 2024, the ABC announced that the entire ABC News division would receive a new look, including for the channel.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] The relaunch occurred on 19 August 2024.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] On 19 May 2025, the ABC announced that the channel will be in high definition again, this time as MPEG-4, alongside ABC Entertains.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] The changes will occur between 11 and 26 June 2025.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] Since the commencement of regular broadcasting, the reaction to the new news channel has been mixed.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] However, Independent Senator Nick Xenophon has blamed the reported $20 million annual cost of the network for cutbacks in ABC TV sports coverage of the SANFL.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] However, the network has seen success with high viewership compared to competitor Sky News Australia, with reach exceeding 2 million viewers weekly, tripling that of Sky News.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] The channel's highest primetime viewership share was 9.5% during the 2016 Federal election coverage on 2 July 2016.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] ABC News programming consists of a mix of live news bulletins, time-shifted repeats of existing ABC News and Current Affairs output, live broadcasts from events (such as Parliament Question Time and selected press conferences), documentaries and factual and arts programming.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] These draw upon the ABC's own resources and those of its partner broadcasters, the BBC, SABC, TVNZ, PBS, NHK, and Al Jazeera English.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] On weekdays, throughout most of the day, straight news programming is presented from one of the studios in Ultimo.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] Live ABC-produced news bulletins air once per hour until 4am AEST/AEDT.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] On weekends, except the *Weekend Breakfast* news block, the channel airs a live news bulletin at the top of almost all hours, which lasts 15 or 30 minutes.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] Occasionally it is a one-minute headline recap.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] A live news hour is featured on Sundays at 7pm.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] ABC News switches to the overnight format at 12:15am AEST/AEDT, without any live newscast until the next morning.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] Specialist and feature programming includes a daily business programme covering the Asia-Pacific region and an international bulletin with Girish Sawlani entitled *The World* presented from ABC Melbourne Studio.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] In addition, *The Business* is shown in an earlier timeslot than currently scheduled on ABC TV.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] On 30 September 2010, the ABC announced the first new programme to be shown on the channel titled *Capital Hill*.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] The political programme, originally hosted by Chris Uhlmann airs Fridays at 5:30pm AEST/AEDT and takes a look at the week's political events and news, as well as feature interviews with the key players of politics.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] It is now broadcast every weekday at 1:00pm AEST/AEDT and is hosted by Greg Jennett (Monday – Thursday) and Matthew Doran (Friday).
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] The BBC World News broadcasts come live into the ABC News channel before being broadcast around Australia.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] About two Al Jazeera English *Newshours* are also broadcast.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] However, since 2018, the overnight programming has slowly refocused on rebroadcasts of the channel's daytime live shows like *The Drum* and *The World* (on weekdays), and ABC's own live news updates have increasingly carried.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] Along with other rolling news channels, the ABC News channel has been criticised for launching into rolling news coverage for "breaking news" where little new information supports such coverage, and just repeating limited information and footage about an event.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] Conversely, the ABC News channel has also been criticised for not turning to rolling coverage.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] The ABC News channel can be streamed online at the ABC's website and on YouTube.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] However, the YouTube stream is made available internationally except for the stream in iView where it is only available in Australia only, and unlike other programming on iView, it is not currently offered as unmetered content by any internet service providers.
[src:auslan/abc-news-australian-tv-channel] The ABC News channel stream is available in medium and high bandwidth varieties on the iView site.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] American Sign Language (ASL) has grammar just like any other sign language or spoken language.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The study of ASL structure dates back to William Stokoe, Dorothy Casterline, and Carl Croneberg in the 1960s.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Since then, linguists have been describing patterns in ASL responsible for creating meaning at all kinds of levels, from the word, to phrases and sentences and beyond.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Not all of these linguists ascribe to the same theoretical framework, using various theories, models, and analyses.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Some analyze the language from a generative linguistics perspective, while others from a cognitive linguistics perspective.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] In ASL morphology, publications have historically categorized morphological processes under two umbrellas: derivational morphology and inflectional morphology.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Derivational morphology is the process by which new units can be created in a language, and like any other language, this process has been observed in a variety of forms in ASL.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] One form of derivational morphology occurs when a change in movement changes the sign's meaning – often between a noun and a verb.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] This may be done either by reduplicating the movement of the verb if the verb has a single movement, or by restraining (making smaller and faster) the movement of the verb if it already has repeated movement.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] For example, the noun CHAIR is derived from the verb SIT through reduplication.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Another way of deriving new words in ASL is via the process of compounding, which often differ in meaning from their constituent signs.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] For example, the signs FACE and STRONG compound to create a new sign FACE^STRONG, meaning 'to resemble'.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Some linguists have analyzed various compounds as a type of suffixation.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Agent nouns may be derived from verbs by adding the sign, or suffix, AGENT and deleting the final hold of the verb, e.g.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Superlatives have also been analyzed as created by a formed by suffixation, e.g.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] For example, Ted Supalla's work on ASL verbs of motion analyzed these signs as consisting of many different affixes, articulated simultaneously according to complex grammatical constraints.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] This differs from the concatenative morphology of many spoken languages, which except for suprasegmental features, such as tone, are tightly constrained by the sequential nature of voice sounds.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Numeral incorporation is another derivational morphological process that has been studied in ASL.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Certain types of signs, for example, those relating to time and age, may incorporate numbers by assimilating their handshape.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] For example, the word for 'week' has handshape /B/ with the weak hand and /1/ with the active hand; the active hand's handshape may be changed to the handshape of any number up to 9 to indicate that many weeks.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Some linguists have analyzed this phenomenon as a type of affixation.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Signs of age, for example, will begin with a touch at the chin.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] They argue that this touch functions as a prefix which completely assimilates with the handshape of the corresponding age number.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] For instance, the word for 'nine' is signed with an /F/ handshape produced ipsilaterally in front of the signer's shoulder.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The chin-touch in 'nine years old' can be analyzed as an affix, which is then produced with this same /F/ handshape.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] For 'three years old', however, the prefix is made with a 3 handshape.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Inflectional morphology adds units of language to other words.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] For example, this would be changing 'watch' to 'watches' or 'watching.' In ASL, the sign may remain unchanged as WATCH, or the meaning may change based on non-manual markers (NMM).
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] ASL morphology demonstrates reduplication and indexicality as well.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] There are about 20 non-manual modifiers in ASL, which are either adjectival or adverbial.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Rather than relying on sequential affixes, ASL makes heavy use of simultaneous modification of signs.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] One example of this is found in the aspectual system (see below); another is *numeral incorporation:* There are several families of two-handed signs which require one of the hands to take the handshape of a numeral.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] For example, drawing the dominant hand lengthwise across the palm and fingers of a flat B hand indicates a number of weeks; the dominant hand takes the form of a numeral from one to nine to specify how many weeks.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] There are analogous signs for 'weeks ago' and 'weeks from now', etc., though in practice several of these signs are only found with the lower numerals.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] ASL also has a system of classifiers which may be incorporated into signs.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] These classifiers are moved through sign space to iconically represent the actions of their referents.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] For example, an ILY hand may 'lift off' or 'land on' a horizontal B hand to sign an aircraft taking off or landing; a 3 hand may be brought down on a B hand to sign parking a car; and a G hand may be brought toward a V hand to represent one person approaching two.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The frequency of classifier use depends greatly on genre, occurring at a rate of 17.7% in narratives but only 1.1% in casual speech and 0.9% in formal speech.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Frames are a morphological device that may be unique to sign languages (Liddell 2004).
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] They are incomplete sets of the features which make up signs, and they combine with existing signs, absorbing features from them to form a derived sign.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] It is the frame which specifies the number and nature of segments in the resulting sign, while the basic signs it combines with lose all but one or two of their original features.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] One, the WEEKLY frame, consists of a simple downward movement.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] It combines with the signs for the days of the week, which then lose their inherent movement.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] For example, 'Monday' consists of an M/O hand made with a circling movement.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] 'MondayWEEKLY' (that is, 'on Mondays') is therefore signed as an M/O hand that drops downward, but without the circling movement.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] A similar ALL DAY frame (a sideward pan) combines with times of the day, such as 'morning' and 'afternoon', which likewise keep their handshape and location but lose their original movement.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Numeral incorporation (see above) also uses frames.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] However, in ASL frames are most productively utilized for verbal aspect.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] While there is no grammatical tense in ASL, there are numerous verbal aspects.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] These are produced by modulating the verb: through reduplication, by placing the verb in an aspectual frame (see above), or with a combination of these means.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] An example of an aspectual frame is the *unrealized inceptive* aspect ('just about to X'), illustrated here with the verb 'to tell'.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] 'To tell' is an indexical (directional) verb, where the index finger (a G hand) begins with a touch to the chin and then moves outward to point out the recipient of the telling.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The handshape throughout the sign is whichever is required by the final hold, in this case a G hand.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The variety of aspects in ASL can be illustrated by the verb 'to be sick', which involves the middle finger of the Y/8 hand touching the forehead, and which can be modified by a large number of frames.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Several of these involve reduplication, which may but need not be analyzed as part of the frame.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] These modulations readily combine with each other to create yet finer distinctions.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Not all verbs take all aspects, and the forms they do take will not necessarily be completely analogous to the verb illustrated here.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Conversely, not all aspects are possible with this one verb.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Aspect is unusual in ASL in that transitive verbs derived for aspect lose their transitivity.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Reduplication is also used for expressing verbal number.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Verbal number indicates that the action of the verb is repeated; in the case of ASL it is apparently limited to transitive verbs, where the motion of the verb is either extended or repeated to cover multiple object or recipient loci.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] (Simple plurality of action can also be conveyed with reduplication, but without indexing any object loci; in fact, such aspectual forms do not allow objects, as noted above.) There are specific dual forms (and for some signers trial forms), as well as plurals.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] If the singular verb uses reduplication, that is lost in the dual and plural forms.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] There are three types of personal name signs in ASL: fingerspelled, arbitrary, and descriptive.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Fingerspelled names are simply spelled out letter-by-letter.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Arbitrary name signs only refer to a person's name, while descriptive name signs refer to a person's personality or physical characteristics.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Once given, names are for life, apart from changing from one of the latter types to an arbitrary sign in childhood.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Name signs are usually assigned by another member of the Deaf community, and signal inclusion in that community.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Name signs are not used to address people, as names are in English, but are used only for third-person reference, and usually only when the person is absent.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The majority of people, probably well in excess of 90%, have arbitrary name signs.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] These are initialized signs: The handshape is the initial of one of the English names of the person, usually the first.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The sign may occur in neutral space, with a tremble; with a double-tap (as a noun) at one of a limited number of specific locations, such as the side of the chin, the temple, or the elbow; or moving across a location or between two locations, with a single tap at each.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Single-location signs are simpler in connotation, like English "Vee"; double-location signs are fancier, like English "Veronica".
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Sam Supalla (1992) collected 525 simple arbitrary name signs like these.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] There are two constraints on arbitrary signs.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] That is, it should not duplicate an existing ASL word.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Second, there should not be more than one person with the name sign in the local community.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] If a person moves to a new community where someone already has their name sign, then the newcomer is obligated to modify theirs.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] This is usually accomplished by compounding the handshape, so that the first tap of the sign takes the initial of the person's first English name, and the second tap takes the initial of their last name.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] There are potentially thousands of such compound-initial signs.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Descriptive name signs are not initialized, but rather use non-core ASL signs.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] They tend to be assigned and used by children, rather like "Blinky" in English.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Parents do not give such names to their children, but most Deaf people do not have deaf parents and are assigned their name sign by classmates in their first school for the deaf.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] At most 10% of Deaf people retain such name signs into adulthood..
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Arbitrary name signs became established very early in the history of ASL.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Descriptive name signs refer to a person's appearance or personality.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The two systems, arbitrary and descriptive, are sometimes combined, usually for humorous purposes.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Hearing people learning ASL are also often assigned combined name signs.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] This is not traditional for Deaf people.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Sometimes people with very short English names, such as "Ann" or "Lee", or ones that flow easily, such as "Larry", may never acquire a name sign, but may instead be referred to with finger-spelling.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Non-Manual Markers (NMM), or Non-Manual Signals (NMS) are communication methods not found in the hands.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] They typically consist of facial expressions and body language.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] NMMs can change the grammar of a sentence.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Not every sign uses non-manual markers, but for many others, these markers determine what sign is being produced.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Some examples of non-manual markers would be the shifting of shoulders, the lowering or raising of eyebrows, a head nod or shake, scrunching of the nose, pursing of the lips, or an open mouth.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] NMMs are important for indicating if a question is being asked.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] For *WH-* questions, the eyebrows are lowered, and for *YES/NO* questions, the eyebrows are raised.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] It is hard to indicate if a question is being asked otherwise without facial indicators.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Another example would be between *I UNDERSTAND* and *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The sign for this is the same; the hand is held up near the forehead with the palm facing the self.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] If the person is nodding and has their eyebrows raised, it means *I UNDERSTAND*.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] If they are shaking their head with eyebrows lowered, it means *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Understanding ASL grammar requires understanding the difference between a signer's dominant and non-dominant hand.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] If a person is right-handed, then their right hand is their dominant hand, and their left hand is their non-dominant hand.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Almost all signs are completed with the more active, dominant hand, while the non-dominant hand serves as a base.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] For signs requiring two hands, the dominant hand performs more of the active component.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] ASL is a subject–verb–object (SVO) language.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] However, OSV is also an accepted sentence form.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The default SVO word order is sometimes altered by processes including topicalization and null elements.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] This is marked either with non-manual signals like eyebrow or body position, or with prosodic marking such as pausing.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] These non-manual grammatical markings (such as eyebrow movement or head-shaking) may optionally spread over the c-command domain of the node which it is attached to.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] However, ASL is a pro-drop language, and when the manual sign that a non-manual grammatical marking is attached to is omitted, the non-manual marking obligatorily spreads over the c-command domain.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The full sentence structure in ASL is [topic] [subject] verb [object] [subject–pronoun–tag].
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Topics and *tags* are both indicated with non-manual features, and both give a great deal of flexibility to ASL word order.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Within a noun phrase, the word order is noun–number and noun–adjective.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] ASL does not have a copula (linking 'to be' verb).
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] In addition to its basic topic–comment structure, ASL typically places an adjective after a noun, though it may occur before the noun for stylistic purposes.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Numerals also occur after the noun, a very rare pattern among oral languages.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Adverbs, however, occur before the verbs.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Most of the time adverbs are simply the same sign as an adjective, distinguished by the context of the sentence.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] When the scope of the adverb is the entire clause, as in the case of time, it comes before the topic.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] ASL makes heavy use of time-sequenced ordering, meaning that events are signed in the order in which they occur.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] For example, for *I was late to class last night because my boss handed me a huge stack of work after lunch yesterday,* one would sign 'YESTERDAY LUNCH FINISH, BOSS GIVE-me WORK BIG-STACK, NIGHT CLASS LATE-me'.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] In stories, however, ordering is malleable, since one can choose to sequence the events either in the order in which they occurred or in the order in which one found out about them.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] It has been claimed that tense in ASL is marked adverbially, and that ASL lacks a separate category of tense markers.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] (1992, 1995) argue that "Tense" (T) is indeed a distinct category of syntactic head, and that the T node can be occupied either by a modal (e.g.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Aspect may be marked either by verbal inflection or by separate lexical items.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] As noted above, in ASL aspectually marked verbs cannot take objects.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] To deal with this, the object must be known from context so that it does not need to be further specified.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] It may be used as the topic of the utterance at hand.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Of these two strategies, the first is the more common.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] A topic sets off background information that will be discussed in the following main clause.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Topicalization is used productively in ASL and often results in surface forms that do not follow the basic SVO word order.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] In order to non-manually mark topics, the eyebrows are raised and the head is tilted back during the production of a topic.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The head is often lowered toward the end of the sign, and sometimes the sign is followed rapidly nodding the head.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Another way topics may be signed is by shifting the body.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The signer may use the space on one side of his/her body to sign the topic, and then shifts to the other side for the rest of the sentence.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] ASL utterances do not require topics, but their use is extremely common.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] They are used for purposes of information flow, to set up referent loci (see above), and to supply objects for verbs which are grammatically prevented from taking objects themselves (see below).
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] However, people tend to want to set up the object of their concern first and then discuss what happened to it.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] There are three types of non-manual topic markers, all of which involve raised eyebrows.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The three types of non-manual topic markers are used with different types of topics and in different contexts, and the topic markings cannot spread over other elements in the utterance.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Topics can be moved from and remain null in the main clause of an utterance, or topics can be base-generated and either be co-referential to either the subject or object in the main clause or be related to the subject of object by a semantic property.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The first type of non-manual marking, topic marking 1 (tm1), is only used with a moved topic.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Tm1 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and head tilted backwards.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] At the end of the sign the head moves down and there is a pause, often with an eye blink, before the sentence is continued.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Topic marking 2 (tm2) and topic marking 3 (tm3) are both used with base-generated topics.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Tm2 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and the head tilted backwards and to the side.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Toward the end of the sign the head moves forward and to the opposite side, and there is a pause and often an eye blink before continuing.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] For tm3 the eyebrows are raised and the eyes are opened wide, the head starts tilted down and jerks up and down, the lips are opened and raised, and the head is nodded rapidly a few times before pausing and continuing the sentence.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Although both tm2 and tm3 accompany base-generated topics, they are used in different contexts.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Tm2 is used to introduce new information and change the topic of a conversation to something that the signer is going to subsequently characterize, while tm3 is used to introduce new information that the signer believes is already known by his/her interlocutor.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Tm2 may be used with any base-generated topic, whereas only topics that are co-referential with an argument in the sentence may be marked with tm3.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] ASL sentences may have up to two marked topics.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Possible combinations of topic types are two tm2 topics, two tm3 topics, tm2 preceding tm1, tm3 preceding tm1, and tm2 preceding tm3.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Sentences with these topic combinations in the opposite orders or with two tm1 topics are considered ungrammatical by native signers.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Relative clauses are signaled by tilting back the head and raising the eyebrows and upper lip.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] This is done during the performance of the entire clause.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] where the brackets here indicate the duration of the non-manual features.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] If the sign 'recently' were made without these features, it would lie outside the relative clause, and the meaning would change to "the dog which chased the cat recently came home".
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Negated clauses may be signaled by shaking the head during the entire clause.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] A topic, however, cannot be so negated; the headshake can only be produced during the production of the main clause.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] In addition, in many communities, negation is put at the end of the clause, unless there is a wh- question word.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] For example, the sentence, "I thought the movie was not good," could be signed as, "BEFORE MOVIE ME SEE, THINK WHAT?
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] There are two manual signs that negate a sentence, NOT and NONE, which are accompanied by a shake of the head.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] There are three types of questions with different constructions in ASL: wh- questions, yes/no questions, and rhetorical questions.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings are grammatical and semantic features that do not include the use of hands.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] They can include mouth shape, eye gazes, facial expressions, body shifting, head tilting, and eyebrow raising.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings can also aid in identifying sentence type, which is especially relevant to our discussion of different types of interrogatives.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Wh-questions can be formed in a variety of ways in ASL.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The wh-word can appear solely at the end of the sentence, solely at the beginning of the sentence, at both the beginning and end of the sentence (see section 4.4.2.1 on 'double-occurring wh-words', or in situ (i.e. where the wh-word is in the sentence structure before movement occurs)).
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Manual wh-signs are also accompanied by a non-manual grammatical marking (see section 4.4.1), which can include a variety of features.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] This non-manual grammatical marking can spread optionally over the entire wh-phrase or just a small part.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Some languages have very few wh-words, where context and discourse are sufficient to elicit the information that one needs.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] ASL has many different wh-words, with certain wh-words having multiple variations.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] A list of the wh-words of ASL can be found below.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] As mentioned above, ASL possesses wh-questions with word initial placement, word final placement, in situ structure, but the most unique style of wh-word occurrence in ASL is where the wh-word occurs twice, copied in final position.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] This doubling can be seen in the table below.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] This doubling provides a useful template to analyze two separate analyses about whether wh-words move rightward or leftward in ASL.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] While some researchers argue for rightward movement in wh- questions such as Aarons and Neidle, others, including Petronio and Lillo-Martin, have argued that ASL has leftward movement and wh- words that appear to the right of the clause move by other processes.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Both analyses agree upon the fact that there is wh-movement present in these interrogative phrases, but it is a matter of what direction the wh-movement is moving in that causes controversy.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The leftward movement analysis is congruent with cross-linguistic data that wh-movement is always leftward.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] It can be seen as the less controversial of the two proposals.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The main arguments presented by the Leftward Wh-movement analysis are: That the spec-CP is on the left, that the wh-movement is leftward, and that the final wh-word in a sentence is a base-generated double.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] This is illustrated in the syntax tree located to the right of this paragraph.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Arguments for leftward movement are based on the facts that if wh-movement in ASL were rightward, ASL would be an exception to cross-linguistic generalizations that wh-movement is leftward.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] It has also been hypothesized that wh-elements cannot be topicalized, as topicalized elements must be presupposed and interrogatives are not.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] This would be detrimental to the rightward analysis, as they are analyzing the doubled wh-word as a 'base generated topic'.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The rightward movement analysis is a newer, more abstract argument of how wh-movement occurs in ASL.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The main arguments for rightward movement begin by analyzing spec-CP as being on the right, the wh-movement as being rightward, and as the initial wh-word as a base-generated topic.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] This can be seen in the syntax tree on the right.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] One of the rightward movement analysis' main arguments is in regards to the non-manual grammatical markings, and their optional spreading over the sentence.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] In ASL the use of non-manual grammatical markings is optional depending on the type of wh-question being asked.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] In the rightward analysis both partial and full spreading of non-manual grammatical markers can be accounted for due to the association with the +WH feature over its c-command domain.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] In the leftward analysis, the partial or full spreading of non manual grammatical markings cannot be accounted for in this same way.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The leftward movement analysis requires wh-marking to extend over the entirety of the question, regardless (which is not what is attested in ASL).
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] In spoken language Yes/no questions will oftentimes differ in their word order from the statement form.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] In ASL, yes/no questions are marked by the non-manual grammatical markings (as discussed in section 4.4.1).
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] This eyebrow raise, slight tilt of the head and lean forward are what indicate that a yes/no question is being asked, without any change in word order from the statement form.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] There is speculation amongst linguists that these non-manual grammatical markings that indicate a yes/no questions are similar to the question intonation of spoken languages.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Yes/no questions differ from wh-questions as they do not differ in word order from the original statement form of the sentence, whereas wh-questions do.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] As well, in yes/no questions, the non-manual marking must be used over the whole utterance in order for it to be judged as a statement opposed to a question.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The yes/no question is the same word order as the statement form of the sentence, with the addition of non-manual grammatical markings.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings are also used for rhetorical questions, which are questions that do not intend to elicit an answer.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] To distinguish the non-manual marking for rhetorical questions from that of yes/no questions, the body is in a neutral position opposed to tilted forward, and the head is tilted in a different way than in yes/no questions.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Rhetorical questions are much more common in ASL than in English.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] [I LIKE]NEGATIVE [WHAT?]RHETORICAL, GARLIC.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] This strategy is commonly used instead of signing the word 'because' for clarity or emphasis.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] PASTA I EAT ENJOY TRUE [WHY?]RHETORICAL, ITALIAN I.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] In ASL signers set up regions of space (loci) for specific referents (see above); these can then be referred to indexically by pointing at those locations with pronouns and indexical verbs.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] That is, they point to their referent, or to a locus representing their referent.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] If the referent is not physically present, the speaker identifies the referent and then points to a location (the *locus)* in the sign space near their body.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] This locus can then be pointed at to refer to the referent.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Theoretically, any number of loci may be set up, as long as the signer and recipient remember them all, but in practice, no more than eight loci are used.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Meier 1990 demonstrates that only two grammatical persons are distinguished in ASL: First person and non-first person, as in Damin.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Both persons come in several numbers as well as with signs such as 'my' and 'by myself'.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Meier provides several arguments for believing that ASL does not formally distinguish second from third person.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] For example, when pointing to a person that is physically present, a pronoun is equivalent to either 'you' or '(s)he' depending on the discourse.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] There is nothing in the sign itself, nor in the direction of eye gaze or body posture, that can be relied on to make this distinction.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] That is, the same formal sign can refer to any of several second or third persons, which the indexic nature of the pronoun makes clear.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] In English, indexic uses also occur, as in 'I need *you* to go to the store and *you* to stay here', but not so ubiquitously.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] In contrast, several first-person ASL pronouns, such as the plural possessive ('our'), look different from their non-first-person equivalents, and a couple of pronouns do not occur in the first person at all, so first and non-first persons are formally distinct.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Personal pronouns have separate forms for singular ('I' and 'you/(s)he') and plural ('we' and 'you/they').
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] These have possessive counterparts: 'my', 'our', 'your/his/her', 'your/their'.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] In addition, there are pronoun forms which incorporate numerals from two to five ('the three of us', 'the four of you/them', etc.), though the dual pronouns are slightly idiosyncratic in form *(i.e.,* they have a K rather than 2 handshape, and the wrist nods rather than circles).
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] These numeral-incorporated pronouns have no possessive equivalents.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Also among the personal pronouns are the 'self' forms ('by myself', 'by your/themselves', etc.).
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] These only occur in the singular and plural (there is no numeral incorporation), and are only found as subjects.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] They have derived emphatic and 'characterizing' forms, with modifications used for derivation rather like those for verbal aspect.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The 'characterizing' pronoun is used when describing someone who has just been mentioned.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] It only occurs as a non-first-person singular form.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Finally, there are formal pronouns used for honored guests.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] These occur as singular and plural in the non-first person, but only as singular in the first person.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] ASL is a pro-drop language, which means that pronouns are not used when the referent is obvious from context and is not being emphasized.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] Within ASL there is a class of indexical (often called 'directional') verbs.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] These include the signs for 'see', 'pay', 'give', 'show', 'invite', 'help', 'send', 'bite', etc.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] These verbs include an element of motion that indexes one or more referents, either physically present or set up through the referent locus system.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] If there are two loci, the first indicates the subject and the second the object, direct or indirect depending on the verb, reflecting the basic word order of ASL.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] For example, 'give' is a bi-indexical verb based on a flattened M/O handshape.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] For 'I give you', the hand moves from myself toward you; for 'you give me', it moves from you to me.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] The verb 'to be in pain' (index fingers pointed at each other and alternately approaching and separating) is signed at the location of the pain (head for headache, cheek for toothache, abdomen for stomachache, etc.).
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] This is normally done in relation to the signer's own body, regardless of the person feeling the pain, but may take also use the locus system, especially for body parts which are not normally part of the sign space, such as the leg.
[src:auslan/asl-name-sign] There are also spatial verbs such as put-up and put-below, which allow signers to specify where things are or how they moved them around.
[src:auslan/asl-phabet] Like SignFont and Stokoe notation, ASL-phabet is a phonemic script, but it has been simplified to the point where there is some ambiguity, that is, one symbol can represent more than one phonemic element (handshape, location or movement).
[src:auslan/asl-phabet] For example, whereas SignFont has 25 letters encoding types of movement, and Stokoe notation has 24, ASL-phabet has just 5.
[src:auslan/asl-phabet] This can result in homographs (more than one sign spelled the same way).
[src:auslan/asl-phabet] All together, ASL-phabet has 22 letters for handshape, 5 for location, and 5 for movement.
[src:auslan/asl-phabet] They are written in that order, left-to-right, with the possibility for several letters of each type, such as two handshape letters for a two-handed sign.
[src:auslan/asl-phabet] Like Stokoe notation (but unlike SignFont), the ASL-phabet does not provide symbols for facial expressions, mouthing, and other aspects of sign language structure, which may make it hard to use for extended text.
[src:auslan/asl-phabet] However, it is sufficient to look up ASL words in an ASL–English dictionary.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Its core components are digits, locatives, marks and movements which are written in a fairly rigid order (though in a fairly flexible configuration) from left to right.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] The order of the writing is from left to right, top to bottom, with locatives or certain marks often beginning words.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Sentences are ended by the full stop mark ().
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Questions in written ASL are denoted by eyebrow marks bounding the question not unlike Spanish's "¿ ?." Question words or wh-questions in ASL can also form the interrogative.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] There are in total 105 characters in ASLwrite with 67 digits, five diacritic marks, twelve locatives, sixteen extramanual marks and five movement marks.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Since its creation, it has evolved to include more digits, locatives, movements and marks as well as modify those already present.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] si5s, a system built from SignWriting, was first proposed by Robert Arnold in his 2007 Gallaudet thesis *A Proposal of the Written System for ASL*.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] The ASLwrite community split from Arnold upon his decision to maintain si5s as a private venture with ASLized after the publication of his and Adrean Clark's book *How to Write American Sign Language*.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Aside from the small, but dedicated, Facebook group of around 470 in July 2023, ASLwrite is rarely used outside such online spaces.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] However, one of the most popular online ASL dictionaries, HandSpeak, has begun to incorporate ASLwrite as the primary written component of ASL definitions.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] ASLwrite is a somacheirographic system meaning that it represents the body (Greek: σῶμα *sôma* 'body') and hands (Greek: χείρ *kheír* 'hand') and relays phonemic information.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] However, it also incorporates logographs (questioning marks) and is featural.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] The general principle is to capture a single ASL word per segment, from left to right, registering non-manual feature(s), location(s), handshape(s), movement(s) and general orientation.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] It imagines the writer/speaker is looking down at their hands or viewing words from the profile such that words can be made either as if seen from straight-on or from one's profile.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] The digibet captures handshape information as well as orientation, movement and some locations.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Locatives are characters that capture location, though handshape diacritics like *edge* do capture some locations such as edge of palm.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Diacritics, such as movements, modify handshapes and can indicate small movements or small orientations.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Movements themselves are fairly flexible in their shapes and orientations, which makes digitising this script difficult.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Frontal or profile locatives – Captures the same location information, just from two perspectives.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] An example (seen on the right) is the shoulder locative is either a shoulder frontal locative that is written above or below the handshape(s).
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Handshapes – Can be written before or after the locative.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] A handshape can be oriented in 360° depending on its location and is written at the end of its movement path if there is one.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Each handshape present is written, and when more than one handshape (of one hand) is written, a movement must be present.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Movements – Larger movements or movements that affect multiple handshapes.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] When a handshape changes without overt movement, the handshapes are written left-to-right with a single movement below, similar to an underline.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Non-manual & punctuation marks – These are questioning marks such as *why*, *who*, *how* and *how*.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] The digibet is composed of handshapes called digits that are modified by diacritics and movements.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] It shares 23 handshapes with ASL's manual alphabet.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Digits are grouped together by features such as +thumb/-thumb or +closed/-closed.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] In practise, there are 67 digits in ASLwrite's digibet, though that number is growing as new digits are added representing diverse handshapes.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Moreover, other languages may adopt this system which would add increasingly more digits.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] There are five diacritics, of which one is a movement diacritic.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Movements are flexible and thus hard to capture in a digital or non-handwritten fashion.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] The movements are diverse and aim to capture the movements of the hands, arms and body.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] There are three points – an **endpoint**, a **firmpoint** and a **contactpoint** –, an **orbit mark**, a **steering** and a **crank mark** as well as the movement mark or line.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] The movement line follows the path of the hand(s) and can be as clean (e.g., – or | ) or as erratic as possible.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] The points denote the end of a handshape's path and the degree to which the motion is made.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] A contactpoint denotes an imaginary or in-the-air point with the contactpoint ending at a location and noted as being a firm ending with the firmpoint.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] The orbit mark indicates a central "point" around which the handshapes orbit; for orbital paths cut short, one would use a steering mark, and for parallel cranking motions, the crank mark would be used.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] The locatives are characters that denote a specific location on or near the signer's body.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] They are presented from a face-on and side-view.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] The two sub-classifications are **frontal** and **profile locatives**.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Non-manual marks vary quite significantly and can only be placed at the beginning or end of words or phrases.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] **Eyebrow marks** are denoted before and after the word(s) in question thus bounding the words that are modified by eyebrow marks.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] They are called: **Raised (), Knit, Wan, Slanted** and **Squint**.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Questioning marks exist in ASL as logographs that denote ASL's wh-questions such as WHO or FOR-FOR.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] They are placed after a closed word's or phrase's second eyebrow mark and can exist as an entire sentence alone.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Mouth marks are characters that relay what action the mouth is doing.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] It is placed inside the first eyebrow mark.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Body movements are non-manual, non-facial features such as **shoulder shift ()** or **head nod**.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] They, as well as **nose crinkle ()**, stand alone and can be inserted anywhere, inside and outside of eyebrow-marked phrases.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] means *Yes?* in ASL composed of , , and where the raised eyebrow marks at the beginning and the end indicate it is a yes/no question, and the hinge mark () denotes that the S handshape digit () makes a nodding motion.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] The circular point at the end is a full stop mark indicating the end of the sentence.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Unlike in English writing, the full stop mark () is employed for all sentences, even questions (as seen here).
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Breaks in the sentence, as seen below, are denoted by the shoulder shift mark ().
[src:auslan/aslwrite] The text on the right is from Chapters 1:2–4 of the Book of Ruth.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] The first quoted text is the verse in English and the second is an ASL gloss.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] Due to the complexity of the writing system and its need for flexibility for movements, it means that producing anything in a digital format is difficult.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] However, there are efforts to create fonts headed by members of its Facebook group, notably looking at proper font creation and using current keyboard characters such as ' } ' or ' _.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] ' to achieve minor forms of communication in ASL over text.
[src:auslan/aslwrite] An example phrase is " }_.U- " which means 'thank you' in ASL.
[src:auslan/auslan] Auslan was recognised by the Australian government as a "community language other than English" and the preferred language of the deaf community in policy statements in 1987 and 1991.
[src:auslan/auslan] However, this recognition has yet to filter through to many institutions, government departments, and professionals who work with deaf people.
[src:auslan/auslan] The emerging status of Auslan has gone hand-in-hand with the advancement of the deaf community in Australia, beginning in the early 1980s.
[src:auslan/auslan] In 1982, the registration of the first sign language interpreters by NAATI, a newly established regulatory body for interpreting and translating, accorded a sense of legitimacy to Auslan, furthered by the publishing of the first dictionary of Auslan in 1989 (Johnston, 1989).
[src:auslan/auslan] Boosted by the 1992 enactment of the federal Disability Discrimination Act, Auslan/English interpreters are also increasingly provided in tertiary education.
[src:auslan/auslan] Today there is a growing number of courses teaching Auslan as a second language, from an elective language subject offered by some secondary schools to a two-year full-time diploma at TAFE.
[src:auslan/auslan] Auslan content on television in Australia is limited.
[src:auslan/auslan] For some time, "Deaf TV", which was entirely in Auslan and was produced by deaf volunteers, aired on community television station Channel 31 in Melbourne.
[src:auslan/auslan] During the COVID-19 pandemic, Auslan experienced a period of increased visibility through press conferences from federal and state leaders and health officials, which invariably featured Auslan interpreters.
[src:auslan/auslan] Since 2020, the ABC News channel's Sunday 5pm bulletin has included Auslan interpretation.
[src:auslan/auslan] Auslan Day is celebrated on 13 April each year.
[src:auslan/auslan] This date was chosen as the anniversary of the publication of the first Auslan dictionary in 1989.
[src:auslan/auslan] The Young Australian of the Year for 2015, Drisana Levitzke-Gray, is a strong proponent of Auslan and, in her acceptance speech using Auslan, called on the Government of Australia, and Australians, to learn and use Auslan as a natural language, as a human right for Australians.
[src:auslan/auslan] Auslan evolved from sign language varieties brought to Australia during the nineteenth century from Britain and Ireland.
[src:auslan/auslan] The earliest record of a deaf Australian was convict Elizabeth Steel, who arrived in 1790 on the Second Fleet ship "Lady Juliana".
[src:auslan/auslan] There is as yet no historical evidence, however, that she used a sign language.
[src:auslan/auslan] One of the first known signing Deaf immigrants was the engraver John Carmichael who arrived in Sydney in 1825 from Edinburgh.
[src:auslan/auslan] He had been to a Deaf school there, and was known as a good storyteller in sign language.
[src:auslan/auslan] Thirty-five years later, in 1860, a school for the deaf was established by another deaf Scotsman, Thomas Pattison—the Royal Institute for Deaf and Blind Children in New South Wales.
[src:auslan/auslan] In Victoria just a few weeks later, the Victorian College for the Deaf was founded by a deaf Englishman, Frederick J Rose, who had been educated at the Old Kent Road School in London.
[src:auslan/auslan] These schools and others had an enormous role in the development of Auslan, as they were the first contact with sign language for many deaf children.
[src:auslan/auslan] Because they were residential boarding schools, they provided ample opportunity for the language to thrive, even though in many schools, signing was banned from the classroom for much of the 20th century.
[src:auslan/auslan] Irish Sign Language (ISL) also had an influence on the development of Auslan, as it was used in Roman Catholic deaf schools until the 1950s, especially in Sydney.
[src:auslan/auslan] The first Catholic school for deaf children was established in 1875 by Irish nuns.
[src:auslan/auslan] As such, like Auslan evolving from BSL, Australian Irish Sign Language (or AISL) was born.
[src:auslan/auslan] Unlike British Sign Language, both ISL and AISL use a one-handed alphabet originating in French Sign Language (LSF), and although this alphabet has now almost disappeared from Australia, some initialised signs from the ISL/AISL manual alphabet are still used in Auslan.
[src:auslan/auslan] The language contact post-secondary education between Australian ISL users and 'Australian BSL' users accounts for some of the dialectal differences seen between modern BSL and Auslan.
[src:auslan/auslan] In more recent times, Auslan has seen a significant amount of lexical borrowing from American Sign Language (ASL), especially in signs for technical terms.
[src:auslan/auslan] Some of these arose from the Signed English educational philosophies of the 1970s and 80s, when a committee looking for signs with direct equivalence to English words found them in ASL and/or in invented English-based signed systems used in North America and introduced them in the classroom.
[src:auslan/auslan] ASL contains many signs initialised from an alphabet which was also derived from LSF, and Auslan users, already familiar with the related ISL alphabet, accepted many of the new signs easily.
[src:auslan/auslan] Tertiary education in the US for some deaf Australian adults also accounts for some ASL borrowings found in modern Auslan.
[src:auslan/auslan] Previously, Auslan had been said to be OSV, but more recent scholars have said that this idea is a false-equivalent of Auslan with spoken languages and that using anchor signs is not the same as word order.
[src:auslan/auslan] In general, word order in Auslan takes into account context and fluidity between signs being used, being less rigid than many spoken languages.
[src:auslan/auslan] Rather, Auslan instead follows the clause/word order of TTC—Time, topic, comment.
[src:auslan/auslan] The frequency of SVO in Auslan may come from code-switching with English (with very high bilingualism for Auslan users), as it is more common with "loan words (signs), English-based idiomatic phrases [and] fingerspelling" as well as by those who learned Auslan later in life.
[src:auslan/auslan] In question phrases, the question word must always be at the end in Auslan in open questions.
[src:auslan/auslan] This word order is the same for both questions and statements, with questions in Auslan formed by either adding a question word at the end of a clause TOM KICKED PETER WHY or using nonmanual features of a questioning expression.
[src:auslan/auslan] Verbs in Auslan which are *depicting signs* use head-marking to show the semantic role of the arguments, rather than subject/object.
[src:auslan/auslan] An example of this is the word *give*, which involves an actor and a recipient.
[src:auslan/auslan] Both of these arguments can be expressed on the verb by using signing space.
[src:auslan/auslan] Verb predicates can be formed by using individual vocabulary words in sequential order (more commonly used by anglophones who speak Auslan as a second language) or using depicting signs, which can "blur" word order, as it allows for multiple signs to be used at once.
[src:auslan/auslan] This is generally a mark of high competence and fluency in the language.
[src:auslan/auslan] Lexicalisation of common predicates is common, and compounding is the most common way that new lexical items are produced.
[src:auslan/auslan] Auslan is a zero-copula language, which means that the verb *to be* is not used at all except when quoting English (in which it is finger-spelt).
[src:auslan/auslan] Auslan replaces copula with interrogatives for certain phrase types, sometimes in this context called "rhetorical questions" or "modifiers", using non-manual features to express that it is a statement rather than a question.
[src:auslan/auslan] The interrogatives of Auslan are more or less direct translations to English ones, with WHY used for this purpose sometimes translated as BECAUSE.
[src:auslan/auslan] Pronouns are established using the signing space, either arbitrary (for non-present people/things) or iconic.
[src:auslan/auslan] For example, "I will give you the doll tomorrow" would be signed as TOMORROW DOLL GIVE, with the sign GIVE starting at the speaker's body and finishing at the receiver's.
[src:auslan/auslan] The use of signing space also makes all pronouns non-gendered.
[src:auslan/auslan] It is sometimes wrongly assumed that English-speaking countries share a single sign language.
[src:auslan/auslan] Auslan is a natural language distinct from spoken or written English.
[src:auslan/auslan] Its grammar and vocabulary often do not have direct English equivalents and vice versa.
[src:auslan/auslan] However, English, as the dominant language in Australia, has had a significant influence on Auslan, especially through manual forms such as fingerspelling and (more recently) Signed English.
[src:auslan/auslan] It is difficult to sign Auslan fluently while speaking English, as the word order may be different, and there is often no direct sign-to-word equivalence.
[src:auslan/auslan] However, mouthing of an English word together with a sign may serve to clarify when one sign may have several English equivalents.
[src:auslan/auslan] In some cases, the mouth gesture that accompanies a sign may not reflect the equivalent translation in English (e.g. a sign meaning "thick" may be accompanied by a mouth gesture that does not resemble any English word).
[src:auslan/auslan] A two-handed manual alphabet, identical to the one used in British Sign Language and New Zealand Sign Language, is integral to Auslan.
[src:auslan/auslan] This alphabet is used for fingerspelling proper nouns such as personal or place names, common nouns for everyday objects, and English words, especially technical terms, for which there is no widely used sign.
[src:auslan/auslan] Fingerspelling can also be used for emphasis, clarification, or, sometimes extensively, by English-speaking learners of Auslan.
[src:auslan/auslan] The proportion of fingerspelling versus signs varies with the context and the age of the signer.
[src:auslan/auslan] A recent small-scale study puts fingerspelled words in Auslan conversations at about 10% of all lexical items, roughly equal to ASL and higher than many other sign languages, such as New Zealand Sign Language.
[src:auslan/auslan] The proportion is higher in older signers, suggesting that the use of fingerspelling has diminished over time.
[src:auslan/auslan] Schembri and Johnston (2007) found that the most commonly fingerspelled words in Auslan include "so", "to", "if", "but" and "do".
[src:auslan/auslan] Some signs also feature an English word's initial letter as a handshape from a one- or two-handed manual alphabet and use it within a sign.
[src:auslan/auslan] For example, part of the sign for "Canberra" incorporates the letter "C".
[src:auslan/auslan] Australasian Signed English was created in the late 1970s to represent English words and grammar, using mostly Auslan signs together with some additional contrived signs, as well as borrowings from American Sign Language (ASL).
[src:auslan/auslan] It was used largely in education for teaching English to deaf children or for *discussing* English in academic contexts, and it is not clear to what extent this continues to be the case.
[src:auslan/auslan] It was thought to be much easier for hearing teachers and parents to learn another mode of English than to learn a new language with a complex spatial grammar such as Auslan.
[src:auslan/auslan] The use of Signed English in schools is controversial with some in the deaf community who regard Signed English as a contrived and unnatural artificially constructed language.
[src:auslan/auslan] Signed English has now been largely rejected by deaf communities in Australia and its use in education is dwindling; however, a number of its signs have made their way into normal use.
[src:auslan/auslan] Unlike oral languages, only a minority of deaf children acquire their language from their parents (about 4 or 5% have deaf parents).
[src:auslan/auslan] Most acquire Auslan from deaf peers at school or later through deaf community networks.
[src:auslan/auslan] Many learn Auslan as a "delayed" first language in adolescence or adulthood, after attempting to learn English (or another spoken/written language) without the exposure necessary to properly acquire it.
[src:auslan/auslan] The deaf community often distinguish between "oral deaf" who grew up in an oral or signed English educational environment without Auslan, and those "*Deaf* Deaf" who learnt Auslan at an early age from deaf parents or at a deaf school.
[src:auslan/auslan] Regardless of their background, many deaf adults consider Auslan to be their first or primary language, and see themselves as users of English as a second language.
[src:auslan/auslan] Auslan exhibits a high degree of variation, determined by the signer's age, educational background, and regional origin, and the signing community is very accepting of a wide range of individual differences in signing style.
[src:auslan/auslan] Standard dialects arise through the support of institutions, such as the media, education, government and the law.
[src:auslan/auslan] As this support has not existed for most sign languages, coupled with the lack of a widely used written form and communications technologies, Auslan has probably diverged much more rapidly from BSL than Australian English has from British English.
[src:auslan/auslan] Auslan was introduced to Papua New Guinea, where it mixed with local or home sign and Tok Pisin to produce Papua New Guinean Sign Language.
[src:auslan/auslan] Sign languages related to Auslan also appear to be used in some other parts of the Asia-Pacific, such as in Fiji.
[src:auslan/auslan] Linguists often regard Auslan as having two major dialects—Northern (Queensland and New South Wales), and Southern (Victoria, Tasmania, South Australia, and Western Australia).
[src:auslan/auslan] The vocabulary of the two dialects traditionally differed significantly, with different signs used even for very common concepts such as colours, animals, and days of the week; differences in grammar appear to be slight.
[src:auslan/auslan] Before schools were established elsewhere, deaf children attended one of these two initial schools, and brought signs back to their own states.
[src:auslan/auslan] As schools opened up in each state, new signs also developed in the dormitories and playgrounds of these institutions.
[src:auslan/auslan] As a result, Auslan users can identify more precise regional varieties (e.g., "Sydney sign", "Melbourne sign", "Perth sign", "Adelaide sign" and "Brisbane sign"), and even vocabulary that may have been unique to individual schools.
[src:auslan/auslan] In a conversation between two strangers, one from Melbourne and the other from Perth, it is likely that one will use a small number of signs unfamiliar to the other, despite both belonging to the same "southern dialect".
[src:auslan/auslan] Signers can often identify which school someone went to, even within a few short utterances.
[src:auslan/auslan] A number of Indigenous Australian sign languages exist, unrelated to Auslan, such as Warlpiri Sign Language and Yolngu Sign Language.
[src:auslan/auslan] They occur in the southern, central, and western desert regions, coastal Arnhem Land, some islands of the north coast, the western side of Cape York Peninsula, and on some Torres Strait Islands.
[src:auslan/auslan] They have also been noted as far south as the Murray River.
[src:auslan/auslan] Deaf Indigenous people of Far North Queensland (extending from Yarrabah to Cape York) form a distinct signing community using a dialect of Auslan; it has features of Indigenous sign languages and gestural systems as well as signs and grammar of Auslan.
[src:auslan/auslan] Auslan has no written form; in the past transcribing Auslan was largely an academic exercise.
[src:auslan/auslan] The first Auslan dictionaries used either photographs or drawings with motion arrows to describe signs; more recently, technology has made possible the use of short video clips on CD-ROM or online dictionaries.
[src:auslan/auslan] SignWriting, however, has its adherents in Australia.
